## âœ… PART 1: NGINX as a Reverse Proxy

---

### ğŸ”§ Step 1: Install NGINX

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y
```

---

### ğŸ”§ Step 2: Remove default site

```bash
sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*
```

---

### ğŸ”§ Step 3: Create new reverse proxy config

```bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/reverse.conf
```

Paste the following (replace `sourceip` with your actual backend server IP like `192.168.80.129`):

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://192.168.80.129;
    }
}
```

---

### ğŸ”§ Step 4: Create symbolic link in `sites-enabled`

```bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/reverse.conf /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
```

---

### ğŸ”§ Step 5: Test and restart NGINX

```bash
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl restart nginx
```

âœ… Now, accessing your NGINX server's IP in a browser will show content from the backend server.

